2) Using Hash Table: [Time: O(n) Space: O(n)]
from collections import defaultdict                        #We use a hashmap (count) to store frequency of values 
class Solution:
    def countBadPairs(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        n = len(nums)
        counter = defaultdict(int)                         #Stores frequency of each value = nums[i] - i . Default value = 0 (no need to check existence)
        good_pairs = 0                                     #Keeps track of total valid (good) pairs
        total_pairs = (n * (n-1)) // 2                     # Formula for total number of pairs
        for i in range(n):
            value = nums[i] - i                            #This is the core trick. Transforms the condition into a comparable value. If two indices have same key → they form a good pair.
            good_pairs += counter[value]                   #How many times have I seen this key before? Each previous occurrence forms a pair with current index. If counter[value] = 3 → current element forms 3 new good pairs
            counter[value] += 1                            #Record that this key has appeared again
        
        return total_pairs - good_pairs

    Key points:
     --> Instead of counting bad pairs directly (hard), we count good pairs (easy) where nums[i] - i == nums[j] - j
     --> Use HashMap for Frequency
     --> good_pairs += count[key] -- Each new element pairs with all previous same keys [ Combinational logic --  If a value appears k times: k * (k - 1) // 2]

